A constant health checking mechanism that attempts to connect to a MongoDB replicaset with an interval of every 30 seconds causes sockets not getting closed properly after calling db.close()

A minimum code sample that could lead to this issue is

```
function healthCheck(callback) {
  MongoClient.connect('mongodb://node1,node2,node3/?replicaSet=repl1', function(err, db) {
    var r = err;

    db.close(true, function(err, result) {
      callback(r);
    });
  });
}

function routine() {
  healthCheck(function(r) {
    console.log(r);
  });

  setTimeout(routine, 30000);
}

routine();
```

I monitored this app running using netstat and an hour made the socket connection grew up to ~400-500 per node.

A workaround I found was to wrap db.close() with a setTimeout of 1 second to give it a delay, as in `setTimeout(function() { db.close(true, function(err, results) { callback(r) }) }, 1000);` with the above code in context. This would greatly help the method to close the connection (with smaller delays I've tried, such as 200ms, it still sometimes doesn't close the connection).

